An old Cherokee is teaching his grandson about life. &ldquo;A fight is going on inside me,&rdquo; he said to the boy.
&ldquo;It is a terrible fight and it is between two wolves. One is evil - he is anger, envy, sorrow, regret, greed, arrogance, self-pity, guilt, resentment, inferiority, lies, false pride, superiority, and ego.&rdquo;
He continued, &ldquo;The other is good - he is joy, peace, love, hope, serenity, humility, kindness, benevolence, empathy, generosity, truth, compassion, and faith.

I&rsquo;ve just finished reading Anne Lamott&rsquo;s Bird by Bird, a wonderfully humourous book full of advice on how to write and how to overcome those challenges all writers face. Here&rsquo;s an excerpt I particularly like:
 &ldquo;But how?&rdquo; my students ask. &ldquo;How do you actually do it?&rdquo;
You sit down, I say. You try to sit down at approximately the same time every day. This is how you train your unconscious to kick in for you creatively.

According to the Wikia Wiki, a wordbit is &ldquo;the smallest deal that bears a meaning. Wordbits are the sound or sounds, sideput, that bear meaning.&rdquo;
Wordbits are the building blocks of language. This website is my small attempt to bring meaning to what we do as writers and hopefully contribute something to the writing &ldquo;blogosphere&rdquo;, if you&rsquo;ll excuse the jargon.
But this website is more than a blog. This is also a place where you can view my on-line portfolio, or check out some resources for other writers (still in progress).
